##WHO declares new outbreak a global pandemic. Is it "better late than never" ? US CDC admits new deaths may be miscounted as flu

On March 11(China Standard Time) , who director-general Tan Desai announced at a regular press conference that the outbreak of new coronavirus pneumonia had become a "pandemic" , he also noted that this could be the first "manageable pandemic" in history, but that it would depend on every decision made by governments, businesses, communities, families and individuals to prevent and control the epidemic.

More than 110 countries outside China have reported new cases of pneumonia, with 4,596 new confirmed cases and 258 new deaths, according to the latest figures released by the World Health Organization (WHO) on Monday. There are now 118,326 patients worldwide.

"In the past two weeks, the number of new cases of pneumonia outside China has increased more than tenfold and the number of countries affected has tripled. In the coming days and weeks, World Health Organization expects the number of cases, deaths and affected countries to rise further,"he said, "given the alarming spread and severity of the epidemic, we are deeply concerned, as are the alarming levels of inaction. "

"Therefore, our assessment is that COVID-19 has pandemic characteristics, " he added, "calling this epidemic a pandemic does not change who's assessment of the threat of this virus, nor does it change what who is doing, and certainly not what countries should be doing. "

Figure | who director-general Tan Desai at a press conference on November 11(Source: Twitter) 

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
There had been a number of voices questioning World Health Organization's delay in declaring the new outbreak a "pandemic" . The Bill Gates said on February 28 that the new coronavirus could be a once-in-a-century "pandemic" ; But World Health Organization was clearly more cautious at the time about using the term "pandemic" to define COVID-19. Because declaring an infectious disease a pandemic would neither provide who with more support and help nor empower it.

As tandesay said at the 11 th press conference: "pandemic is not a word to be used lightly or lightly. ". If misused, the word can cause undue panic or lead to the false belief that fighting is futile and that we are left to our fate, leading to unnecessary suffering and death."

And with reference to earlier outbreaks in countries such as China, South Korea and Singapore, the epidemic has been brought under control to a certain extent, which was one of the factors taken into account earlier by WHO. "By taking decisive early action, we can slow down the spread of the virus and prevent infection. Most infected people will recover, " Tamdesay cautioned, "focusing only on the total number of reported global cases and the total number of countries with confirmed cases may be biased. More than 70 per cent of the more than 80,000 cases reported in China have been discharged, and 93 per cent of the cases reported so far have come from just four countries."

Figure | World Health Organization global outbreak data (Source: Who Website)

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
So, with the development of NCP only now declaring a "pandemic" , is World Health Organization's tissue reacting too slowly?

In previous press conferences, World Health Organization has stressed that the world should be prepared for the possibility of a global pandemic. The question should not focus on what word to use to describe an outbreak, but whether to use a "pandemic" would not interfere with any single infection and would not help save anyone's life. It is time for all nations, communities, families and individuals to focus on getting ready to contain the epidemic.

In addition, the "public health emergency of international concern" (PHEIC) , announced as early as January 30, is already the WHO's highest alert level for the global epidemic. There are no regulations governing the extent to which a pandemic is expressed. As a specialized agency of the United Nations and the largest Intergovernmental Health Organization, who has no authority over how countries or regions should operate in the face of an epidemic and can only make calls and recommendations.

While concerned and alarmed by the extent of the global spread of the new coronavirus, who also expressed dissatisfaction with the level of inaction on the part of multinational leaders in responding to the outbreak. "We are also shocked by the level of inaction on the part of some leaders, " Tandser said. "In dealing with the epidemic, some countries lack capacity, some countries lack resources, and some countries lack determination. "

It is worth mentioning that this is the world's first "pandemic" caused by coronavirus. Previously, SARS (Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome) and Mers (Middle East Respiratory Syndrome) , both caused by coronavirus, had not been declared a global pandemic. When SARS hit China in 2003, World Health Organization also adopted the definition of "epidemic area" at the time. In 2005, after World Health Organization implemented the IHR, PHEIC became the highest level of global health security.

Figure | map of affected countries and deaths as of 31 July 2009(Source: Who)

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The Spanish flu of 1918-19, which killed between 20 and 40 million people worldwide, was one of the "pandemics" of history. The latest is the 2009 influenza a (H1N1) , the first public health emergency of international concern (PHEIC) since the implementation of the international health regulations in 2005.

As of mid March 2010, the then H1N1 flu epidemic had sickened 59 million Americans, hospitalized 265,000 and killed 12,000, according to U.S. CDC estimates. In addition, 186 countries (and territories) have confirmed cases of influenza a (H1N1) globally and 72 countries (and territories) have reported deaths (data updated in January 2020) .

Following the WHO Declaration of influenza a as a pandemic, which resulted in a short period of concentrated resources for Vaccine Development, the disease later proved to have limited impact, this has led many to criticise the WHO's response as "excessive" . "In 2009, it was kind of a joke to block a virus that had a lower mortality rate than the flu, " YC Huang, senior fellow for Global Health at the Council on Foreign Relations, told Deeptech, "The announcement of the pandemic was scary and took a lot of resources. Especially in Asian countries, a lot of resources were spent on containment policies that turned out to be not really necessary. "

Dr. Margaret Chan, who's director general at the time, then addressed a letter to the BMJ in response to questions about "why H1N1 was declared a pandemic and what indicators to use" . These include a new viral infection that most people have no immunity to, and that has emerged and spread around the world. While pandemics may look similar in some respects to ordinary influenza, they may have other features that may be quite different, such as seasonal influenza and pandemics that can cause infections throughout the age range, in most cases, it leads to self-limited disease, in which the patient recovers completely without treatment. However, the proportion of severe cases of "pandemic" disease is likely to be higher and not seasonal in duration, with outbreaks even in the summer.

"In fact, the definition of pandemic itself is very vague. A sustained, large-scale, worldwide epidemic of infectious diseases is a pandemic. The operation is flexible, " Huang said.

Therefore, after China, the first country to have an outbreak, took measures of such magnitude and intensity to prevent the spread of the epidemic and achieved results, it simply criticized World Health Organization for not declaring the new outbreak a "pandemic" , to some extent, it is hard to convince people that it has delayed the preparation of epidemic prevention and control in other countries.

US President Donald Trump's latest decision on the outbreak was announced at 9 pm US time on 11 March (Source: CNN)

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
In the past, the World Health Organization Organization also considered the important point is that if the declaration of a pandemic, will have a great impact on global economic, political and social life. While it may go some way towards urging governments and relevant health agencies to take a more serious and cautious approach to the epidemic, it may also further exacerbate public fears and increase violence and discrimination, or the risk of social, economic, and other crisis events.

Affected by international oil prices, the US stock market opened on March 9 and hit the fuse, allowing the world to witness a historic decline. Then, on March 10th, the market rebounded. But on March 11, U.S. stocks plunged again, with all three major indexes plunging more than 1,400 points and plunging as much as 6 percent into a technical bear market; only the health care sector was less volatile. "The impact on the U.S. economy has been exaggerated, " U.S. President Donald Trump Buffett told reporters on March 10, adding that the situation in the oil and coronavirus markets has been compounded, is a "combination punch" for financial markets. But the situation is not as dire as it was in 2008.

Donald Trump spoke at 9 am this morning at the China Standard Time about the new coronavirus outbreak in the United States, after the WHO declared it a "pandemic" . He announced that the US would suspend all travel from Europe for the next 30 days (the UK is not subject to the travel ban) from the early hours of Friday, and would give tax and mortgage-related benefits to small businesses and individuals. He also called on Congress to cut payroll taxes, only to be opposed by lawmakers from both parties. Washington, the U. S. capital, its mayor also announced on the same day that Washington officially entered a state of emergency and a public health emergency.

On the same day, the U. S. House of Representatives held a hearing on the new coronavirus. In response to the serious shortage of new coronaviruses in the United States, a member of Congress asked: "Are there any cases in the United States that are thought to have died from influenza that may actually have died from infection with the new coronaviruses? " The director of the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention responded, there have been cases of death from new coronaviruses that were originally diagnosed as having the flu.

At the same time, the impact of the new crown disease continues to unfold in more ways than one. The National Basketball Association (NBA) announced on March 12 that it was suspending all future games due to the player's diagnosis. The China Standard Time will announce when the rematch will be held. In Europe, Serie A has been suspended, La Liga and Ligue 1 have decided to play without fans, and several European football matches have been postponed. It has been revealed that UEFA has been discussing the need to postpone this year's European Cup, as there is no guarantee that it will open this summer.

After declaring a "pandemic, " The WHO director-general stressed to the media: "people should not be afraid because of the new crown epidemic into a global pandemic. ". The emergence of this term does not mean that we have to give up the fight and decided to co-exist with the virus. We say it could be a pandemic, but we can't just do nothing about it. It can be contained."

Mike Ryan, who's executive director of emergency response, was on hand to urge: "All countries need to immediately disclose their strategies to deal with the new outbreak. " Ryan said he would not name specific countries. "The answers are in your hearts. "

"This is not just a public health crisis, it's a crisis of everything, so everyone has to be part of the fight, " Tan stressed at the press conference. He added that the basic elements of a response were the same for all countries:

* Emergency Response Mechanism;
* Risk Communication and public participation;
* Present case and contact tracing;
* Public health measures such as hand hygiene, Respiratory Etiquette and social distance;
* Laboratory testing;
* Prepare patients and hospitals for treatment;
* Prevention and control of infection;
* And the entire community and government.
